place_intro:
Sublian Festival is Batangas City's two-week foundation celebration that wraps up every July 23, the same day the city marks its cityhood anniversary. The name comes from the Subli, a centuries-old devotional dance from the Batangas heartland that the city revived in 1988 to keep the tradition from disappearing. What you see on the streets today is part civic parade, part cultural revival, part neighborhood fiesta.

The host is Batangas City, the provincial capital sitting at the southern end of CALABARZON, about two and a half to three hours from Manila by bus through the STAR Tollway. It is best known as a jump-off point for Anilao diving, Verde Island, and the ferry terminal to Mindoro, but during July the focus shifts inland to the City Hall Complex, the People's Quadrangle, and the streets around the Basilica of the Immaculate Conception.

For a DIY traveler, this is one of those festivals where you can pair a city culture day with a beach weekend without changing buses. Show up for the July 23 street dance in the morning, then catch a jeep down to the port or a bus to Mabini in the afternoon."}

what_unique:
What sets Sublian apart from the louder, more touristy Philippine festivals is that the dance at its center is not a choreographed showpiece invented for tourism. The Subli is an actual devotional dance with roots traced to 1595 in Alitagtag, performed historically in front of the Mahal na Poong Santa Krus. The stooped posture of the male dancers, the bamboo castanets, the wide-brimmed salakot hats on the women, all of it carries meaning that predates the festival by almost four centuries.

The second thing that makes it distinct is the food side. Most fiestas have food stalls. Sublian has Lupakan at Awitan, where you can actually watch people pound nilupak in big wooden mortars while folk singers go at it beside them, and a separate Malunggayan Fiesta built around moringa, which is more of a Batangas pantry staple than a tourist dish.

Third, because it is tied to cityhood and not just to a saint's feast, you get a civic and religious program mixed together. Floral offerings, awarding of outstanding Batanguenos, harana nights, and free concerts from GMA and ABS-CBN karavans all run inside the same two weeks."}

why_go:
Adivay is the easiest way to see all 13 Benguet municipalities in one place without renting a 4x4 and driving the Halsema Highway for a week. The grand parade alone gives you a side-by-side look at the dress, music, and food of the Ibaloi, Kankanaey, Kalanguya, and other groups of the province. For travelers who only know Baguio, this is a much closer look at Cordillera life than anything you will see on Session Road.

The food and produce angle is the other big draw. The agri-tourism fair is where the strawberry farmers, coffee roasters, and highland vegetable growers actually set up shop, so it is also a chance to taste arabica from Tublay and Atok or pick up etag, the local cured pork, straight from the maker. Cooking demos and farm tours run on the side, and the strawberry farm a few minutes away stays open for picking.

Third reason: November weather in La Trinidad is one of the best windows of the year. The rains have eased, the air is cool at around 15 to 22 C, and the fiesta gives the town a reason to stay open late. Combined with a cheap jeep ride from Baguio, it makes for a low-effort, high-reward weekend."}
